    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_592525076" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/592525076" />
    <a title="Olivia" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/16904705-olivia"><img alt="Olivia" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/592525076?book_show_action=true">Apr 16, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Olivia" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Olivia" href="/user/show/16904705-olivia">Olivia</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
                  <em>
                    This review has been hidden because it contains spoilers. To view it,
                    <a href="#" onclick="Effect.toggle(&#39;reviewTextContainer592525076&#39;); return false;">click here.</a>
                  </em>
              <span id="reviewTextContainer592525076" class="readable"
                    style="display:none"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3156726380193101351">Having read a couple other of Donna Jo Napoli&apos;s books I have to say that she is a very good young adult author. I first picked up Beast thinking it was Beastly (since the new movie had come out recently). After I read the description on the book however I realized it was something different, but not completely. <br/>Beast is the story of a Persian prince named Orasmyn who is turned into a lion. The lion is in sharp contrast with his human personality. Prince Orasmyn flourishes in his higher status. H</span>
  <span id="freeText3156726380193101351" style="display:none">Having read a couple other of Donna Jo Napoli's books I have to say that she is a very good young adult author. I first picked up Beast thinking it was Beastly (since the new movie had come out recently). After I read the description on the book however I realized it was something different, but not completely. <br />Beast is the story of a Persian prince named Orasmyn who is turned into a lion. The lion is in sharp contrast with his human personality. Prince Orasmyn flourishes in his higher status. He is a highly talented gardener and somewhat of a sensitive/immature person. His family has no idea of his transformation and tries to kill him, so he is forced to flee. He then struggles greatly living a lion life. Napoli include scenes of very beast-like behavior. Prince Orasmyn's internal conflicts are immense as he battles with the raw instincts of the lion body and his prince-like nature. <br />He can no longer handle living in the wild, and so flees to France and takes refuge in an abandoned castle, eventually creating a flourishing rose garden.<br />Long story shorter: a girl falls in love with him and he is transformed back.<br /><br />Like I said, something different, but not completely. I enjoyed this fresh take on the famous Beauty and the Beast tale. I appreciated how real Napoli made it seem that Prince Orasmyn actually was a lion. It was interesting to see the rawness of a beast. It was easy to make connections between our struggles as humans to keep our moral standards when challenged with just completely letting go of ourselves. I think we all have times where we let our natural instincts (usually our raw emotions, like anger or sadness) take control over actions. It is not always (or perhaps never) as extreme as it is in the book, but I think we all can relate to the internal conflicts that Orasmyn is battered with. In the book he struggles with keeping his Islamic faith, and unlike other versions I have seen and read, I really felt like the beast took control of Orasmyn sometimes. <br /><br />Napoli starts off the story with this:<br />"For help on... matters of Islam and Persian history to matters of India and wildlife.. I thank..." she then goes on to list names.<br />Throughout the book there are many aspects of Islam and Persian facts that are included. In the beginning you learn a lot about the folklore (as it was a wicked fairy, or pari, that curses him) as well as the religious rituals performed. The use of Farsi and Arabic is continued throughout the book, adding an interesting spice of language to the reading.<br /><br />A little about the author: Donna Jo Napoli earned her Ph.D in linguistics, and since then has taught at multiple university as a linguistics professor. This explains the French/Farsi/Arabic words throughout Beast. Along with other books, she authored one titled Zel, another version of Rapunzel. <br /><br />All in all Beast was an interesting tale. Little magic except for the first magical transformation is used in the book, making it seem more real than the usual accounts of Beauty and the Beast. It is a young adult novel, and it definitely feels like one, but who doesn't enjoy a good story?</span>
  <a data-text-id="3156726380193101351" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

