  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2040224168" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2040224168" />
    <a title="Kate" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/104823-kate"><img alt="Kate" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1527527813p2/104823.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2040224168?book_show_action=true">Jul 01, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kate" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kate" href="/user/show/104823-kate">Kate</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Audio CD 9781402519680" href="/book/show/631529.Beast">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/104823-kate?shelf=fairytales-and-mythology">fairytales-and-mythology</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/104823-kate?shelf=2017">2017</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/104823-kate?shelf=age-ya">age-ya</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/104823-kate?shelf=audiobooks">audiobooks</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2040224168" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11564323792335873043">After Prince Orasmyn of Persia incorrectly observes halal in the butchering of a camel, he is given a prophecy: he will be slain by his own father. Orasmyn tries to outsmart the prophecy and warns his father not to kill any human being on his hunt the following day, but then Orasmyn is transformed into a lion and given the clue that the spell would be broken with the love of a woman. In order to escape his fate yet again, Orasmyn runs away to India, then to France, where he attempts to lure a wo</span>
  <span id="freeText11564323792335873043" style="display:none">After Prince Orasmyn of Persia incorrectly observes halal in the butchering of a camel, he is given a prophecy: he will be slain by his own father. Orasmyn tries to outsmart the prophecy and warns his father not to kill any human being on his hunt the following day, but then Orasmyn is transformed into a lion and given the clue that the spell would be broken with the love of a woman. In order to escape his fate yet again, Orasmyn runs away to India, then to France, where he attempts to lure a woman to break the spell with roses.<br /><br />I downloaded this and <i>Of Beast and Beauty</i> from the AudioSYNC program. Both were retellings of "Beauty and the Beast," and both fell flat for me. This one did actually follow the familiar story. At first I thought, <i>Okay, Beauty and the Beast set in Persia, that could be interesting.</i> But why change the origins of the Beast, when the story ends up back in France? The change made little sense to me, as did the exact reasoning as to why the prince was cursed. I'm not hugely familiar with halal, and since the prince seemed to be doing everything with care and precision I didn't understand what had gone wrong (the summary mentions helping out a servant, apparently something to do with the camel being deformed? which doesn't exactly seem to be as bad as the original Beast who is cursed for being unkind and selfish). In the beginning, thinking this story was going to continue to take place in the Middle East, all the details about Islam were interesting - but essentially they turned out to not mean a whole lot for the plot. Orasmyn's sporadic prayers (as a lion) and his ingestion of non-halal meat show him as being even less religious, so why then does he end up breaking the curse?? <br /><br />Far too much of the story centers around the Beast practicing being a lion and getting all aroused by lionesses, and about how he goes about preparing some abandoned castle in France with roses for a random woman to discover. If you want a breakdown: <br /><br />Disc/part 1: Learn about Islam<br />Disc/part 2: Learn about how to be a lion<br />Disc/part 3: Mostly fail at being a lion <br />Disc/part 4: Travel over continents carrying a book in his mouth, never noticed by humans<br />Disc/part 5: Prepare castle for unsuspecting woman, Belle's father shows up and meets the lion who can write in the dirt<br />Disc/part 6: Belle and the lion live in the castle together and fall in love in almost exactly the same way as the Disney movie (by reading books and Belle slurping up liquids with her hands so the Beast doesn't feel self-conscious). <br /><br />If this entire story had taken place in Persia, or the curse had made sense, or the curse had been broken in such a way that made sense with the reason why the curse was placed (e.g. the prince is cursed for not allowing in a guest, the beast must then learn how to be a good host to a guest/prisoner), I probably would have enjoyed this more. The prince was already a kind person! As it was, my favorite character in the whole novel was the fox kit that the Beast doesn't kill to keep for a pet for Belle. The narration was also awkwardly slow, with long pauses between paragraphs and sentences.</span>
  <a data-text-id="11564323792335873043" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

<tr class="no_border feedFooterReview" id="update_comment_stuff_Review2040224168">
  <td colspan="2">
